According to shrine tradition, it was initially enshrined by {{ill|Prince Sakaibe no Kurohiko|ja|坂合黒彦皇子|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prince Sakaibe no Kurohiko|qq=|1=Prince Sakai no Kurohiko|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11429115}} on a ridge of the Sarashina mountains. However, following a landslide caused by an earthquake in the third year of the [[:en:Ninna|Ninna era]] (887 CE), the shrine was relocated to the mountain's base.

The shrine is referred to as "Wakamiya" in the [[:en:The Tale of the Heike|Heike Monogatari]], specifically in relation to an event in the first year of the [[:en:Yōwa|Yōwa era]] when {{ill|Kiso Yoshinaka|ja|木曽義仲|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kiso Yoshinaka|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 源義仲|1=Minamoto no Yoshinaka|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q1139202}} reportedly "prostrated himself before Hachiman Shrine." It was known as Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine until the [[:en:Hōreki|Hōreki era]] (1757 CE), when it assumed its current name. By 1759, records of the [[:en:Matsushiro Domain|Matsushiro Domain]] noted the shrine’s landholdings at three ''koku''.

Before the {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離令|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu bunri|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 神仏分離}} (separation of Shinto and Buddhism), the shrine was associated with a [[:en:Shingon Buddhism|Shingon sect temple]] known as Wakamiya Hachiman Jingū-ji.

<gallery>
File:Sarashina-jinja torii.jpg|Torii
File:Sarashina-jinja 2.jpg|Main shrine building
File:Sarashina-jinja cenotaph.jpg|{{ill|Cenotaph for loyal souls|ja|忠魂碑|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Cenotaph for loyal souls|qq=}}
</gallery>

* '''Treasure Tower (Hōkyōintō):''' The grounds contain an ancient stone pagoda inscribed with the year {{ill|Eiwa era|ja|永和|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Eiwa era|qq=|1=Eiwa|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11131293}} 2 (1378 CE). It is believed to mark the burial site of 45 local warriors who pledged their loyalty to Prince [[:en:Prince Munenaga|Morinaga]] and prepared for death before heading to battle. It was designated a tangible cultural property of the city in 1988.
* '''Earthworks:''' The northern and eastern sides of the shrine grounds retain traces of medieval fortifications, possibly linked to a {{ill|Southern Court (Japan)|ja|南朝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Southern Court (Japan)|qq=|1=Southern Dynasties|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q1206988}} loyalist stronghold.
* '''Slender Bronze Sword:''' Discovered during the Edo period in the nearby {{ill|Yazuka Ruins|ja|箭塚遺跡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yazuka Ruins|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, this sword became a sacred treasure of the shrine. It drew attention from historians for demonstrating that bronze cultures from [[:en:Northern Kyushu|Northern Kyushu]] extended far beyond the {{ill|Kansai region|ja|近畿圏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kansai region|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 京阪神|1=Keihanshin|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q1149484}}. It was designated a tangible cultural property of the city in 1988.
* '''Torii Gate:''' The current torii faces east towards the {{ill|Chikuma River|ja|千曲川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chikuma River|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 信濃川|1=Shinano River|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q734455}}, which historically marked the rear of the shrine. The traditional approach was from the west, via the mountains and the ancient Hachioji-san Manji Pass.

The shrine once served the worship needs of the three former villages of Wakamiya, Kurohiko, and Shibahara. Of these, Kurohiko Village, with a population of 1,000 non-agricultural households, was reportedly devastated and dispersed by frequent floods during the {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|戦国時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sengoku period|qq=|1=Sengoku Period (Japan)|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q117415390}}. The names of Kurohiko and Wakamiya are thought to derive from the deeds of the two princes linked to the shrine's origins.

